{{head|fr|particles}}

# {{lb|fr|literary}} [[not]] (used alone to negate a verb, now chiefly with only a few particular verbs: see [[#usage notes|usage notes]])
#* '''1713''', {{w|Voltaire}}, letter, Dec 1713:
#*: {{quote|fr|Je '''ne''' sais si je dois vous appeler Monsieur ou Mademoiselle {{...}}.|I don't know if I should call you Mr or Miss.}}
#* {{quote-text|fr|year=1826|author=w:Victor Hugo|title=Bug-Jargal|section=XXXVIII
|passage=Le prince de France nous aime, celui d'Espagne '''ne''' cesse de nous secourir.|t=The prince of France loves us, that of Spain never stops helping us.}}
#* {{quote-text|fr|year=1868|author=w:Emile Zola|title=Madeleine Férat
|passage=Je '''n{{'}}'''ose te jurer que je t'aime toujours, parce que je sens bien que tu ne me croirais pas.|t=I dare not swear that I still love you, for I sense that you would not believe me.}}
#* {{quote-text|fr|year=1943|author=w:Jean-Paul Sartre|title=Réflexions sur la question juive
|passage=Mais je ne le crois pas : un homme qui trouve naturel de dénoncer des hommes '''ne''' peut avoir notre conception de l'humain {{...}}.|t=But I don't think so: a man who finds it natural to denounce men cannot have our idea of being human.}}
#* {{quote-text|fr|year=1963|author=w:Françoise Hardy|title=L'Amour s'en va
|passage=L'amour s'en va, et le tien '''ne''' saurait durer.|t=Love goes away, and yours will '''not''' be able to last.}}
# [[not]], [[no]] (used before a verb, with a coordinating negative element usually following; see Usage Notes, below)
#* {{quote-text|fr|year=1851|author=w:Henri Murger|title=Le pays latin
|passage=Je '''ne''' sais rien de plus odieux que l'hypocrisie.|t=I don't know anything more odious than hypocrisy.}}
#* {{quote-text|fr|year=1998|author=w:Michel Houellebecq|title=Les Particules Élémentaires
|passage=Bruno se rendit compte qu'il '''ne''' serait jamais accepté par les ''hippies'' {{...}}.|t=Bruno realised that he'd never be accepted by the hippies.}}
#* {{quote-journal|fr|journal=Le Monde|date=3 May 2012
|passage="Il '''n{{'}}'''y a pas eu un truc auquel on '''ne''' s'attendait pas", affirme Stéphane Le Foll.|t="There wasn't anything we weren't expecting," stated Stéphane Le Foll.}}
# {{n-g|Used in a subordinate clause before a subjunctive verb (especially when the main verb expresses doubt or fear), to provide extra overtones of doubt or uncertainty (but not negating its verb); the so-called "pleonastic" or "expletive" ''ne''.}}
#* {{quote-text|fr|year=1829|author=w:Victor Hugo|title=Le Derner Jour d'un Condamné|section=XXVII
|passage=Ah! mes cheveux blanchiront avant que ma tête '''ne''' tombe!|t=Oh! My hair will go white before my head falls!}}
#* {{quote-text|fr|year=1837|author=w:George Sand|title=Mauprat
|passage=Oui, mais je crains qu'elle '''ne''' soit plus malade qu'elle '''ne''' l'avoue, repartit l'abbé.|t="Yes, but I think she might be more ill than she's letting on," the priest replied.}}
# {{n-g|In comparative clauses usually translated with the positive sense of the subsequent negative}}
#: {{ux|fr|Apprendre le français est plus facile qu'on '''ne''' pense.|Learning French is easier than you (might) think.}}

====Usage notes====
* Typically, {{m|fr||ne}} follows the subject and is itself followed by the verb and:
** a negative adverbial ({{m|fr|pas||not; don't/doesn't}}, {{m|fr|plus||no more, no longer}}, {{m|fr|jamais||never}},  (now literary) {{m|fr|guère||hardly}}, or (now obsolete) {{m|fr|point||not a bit}});
** a nominal element modified by a negative determiner ({{m|fr|aucun}} or {{m|fr|nul}}, both meaning "no", "not a") — note that these phrases can take on nominal, pronominal or adverbial functions;
** More mobile are negative pronouns, the most common being {{m|fr|personne||nobody}} and {{m|fr|rien||nothing}}, which will follow {{m|fr||ne}} and the verb if they function as the object complement of that verb, but if they are the subject of a given clause, they will usually sit at its head:
*: {{ux|inline=1|fr|Personne ne s'en souviendra demain.|Nobody will remember about it tomorrow.}}
*: {{ux|inline=1|fr|Rien ne le dérange.|Nothing bothers him.}}
* In literary French (i.e., the most formal variety of the written language) certain verbs can be negated with {{m|fr||ne}} alone (without another negating element like {{m|fr|pas}}). Nowadays, this list is restricted chiefly to the verbs {{m|fr|pouvoir}}, {{m|fr|savoir}}, {{m|fr|cesser}}, {{m|fr|oser}}, and {{m|fr|daigner}}. Less formal registers still require coordination with another negative element.
* In colloquial (i.e., spoken) French, {{m|fr||ne}} is often omitted, leaving the other negating element ({{m|fr|pas}}, {{m|fr|plus}}, {{m|fr|rien}}, {{m|fr|personne}}, etc.) to indicate the sentence's negative state on its own (unless more than one of these elements is already present).
*: {{ux|inline=1|fr|Je veux pas ça.|I don't want that.}}
*: {{ux|inline=1|fr|Il attend personne.|He's not waiting for anyone.}}
*: {{ux|inline=1|fr|J'en ai plus besoin.|I don't need it anymore.}}
*: {{ux|inline=1|fr|On va nulle part.|We're not going anywhere.}}
: In some regions, {{m|fr||ne}} has disappeared from spoken language either entirely or nearly so. Even when it ''is'' included in spoken form, the weak "e" is often elided, causing the remaining {{IPAchar|/n/}} to assimilate into nearby words. Compare a few possible versions of the above example, {{m|fr||Je veux pas ça}}, more or less rising in levels of formality:
:: {{lang|fr|J' veux pas ça.}} {{IPAchar|/ʒ‿vø pɑ sa/}}
:: {{lang|fr|Je veux pas ça.}} {{IPAchar|/ʒə vø pɑ sa/}}
:: {{lang|fr|Je n' veux pas ça.}} {{IPAchar|/ʒə‿n.vø pɑ sa/}}
:: {{lang|fr|Je ne veux pas ça.}} {{IPAchar|/ʒə nə vø pɑ sa/}}
